Leaderboard

Accuracy Metric : FNIR“>FNIR (i.e.,”miss rate") at an FPIR of 0.01(± 90% confidence)
Dataset: Operational Dataset 4th pull
Samples used: Both eyes
Enrolled Population: 500 thousand people
Enrollment Method: One enrollment session per person

The number after the ± indicates either the 90% confidence interval (for accuracy) or the standard deviation (for times).

Detection-Error Trade-off Plots

Core accuracy for the identification task can be characterized by Detection-error trade-off (DET) plots. Generally, curves lower down in a DET plot correspond to more accurate matchers. The plots are interactive through the use of the Plotly.js graphing library.


Dataset: Operational Dataset 4th pull
Samples used: Both eyes
Enrolled Population: 500 thousand people
Enrollment Method: One enrollment session per person

Dataset: Operational Dataset 4th pull
Samples used: One eye
Enrolled Population: 1 million irides
Enrollment Method: One enrollment session per person

Rank-based Accuracy

Rank-based metrics quantify accuracy for closed-set applications, where it can be guaranteed that every searched individual is enrolled. The rank 10 “hit rate” is the fraction of searches that return the correct result within the top 10 candidates. The miss rate is one minus the hit rate.

Dataset: Operational Dataset 4th pull
Samples used: Both eyes
Enrolled Population: 500 thousand people
Enrollment Method: One enrollment session per person

Computation Time

Computation times are measured as the the elapsed real time (i.e., “wall clock” time) as opposed to CPU time. Timing estimates were computed on unloaded machines with only a single process dedicated to biometric operations. The test machines are Dell PowerEdge M910 blades with Dual Intel Xeon X7560 2.3 GHz CPUs (with eight cores per processor).
Dataset: Operational Dataset 4th pull
Samples used: Both eyes
Enrolled Population: 500 thousand people
Enrollment Method: One enrollment session per person

Demographic Factors

Certain demographic characteristics might influence iris recognition behavior. The figures below show rank one miss rates broken out by race, sex, and eye colour. The error bars represent 95% confidence intervals. Eye colour and race do not appear to strongly covary with the rank 1 miss rate. Matchers may have a harder time identifying females than males.


Dataset: Operational Dataset 4th pull
Samples used: One eye
Enrolled Population: 1 million irides
Enrollment Method: One enrollment session per person

Some consolidation of field values was necessary to improve statistical power. Eye colour was simplified to either light (grey, blue, or green) or dark (brown or black). Some subjects were labeled as being neither male nor female. Meaningful results for these categories could not be obtained because their sample sizes are too small. For the same reason, results for races other than white and black are not shown. The precise definitions of race, sex, and eye colour used here can be found in EBTS version 10.0.

Automated Quality Assessment

Participant submissions are allowed to assign quality values to iris samples. The participants who opted to do so are Idemia, Neurotechnology. The concept of an error-reject curve was first proposed in PAMI Vol 28 Issue 4. The authors propose that an effective quality assessor should produce values that positively correlate with recognition accuracy. Discarding the poorest quality samples should therefore reduce identification failures.

The figure below demonstrates that the rank 1 miss rate can be reduced by roughly 20% by discarding just 1% of the poorest quality samples. Presumably, this 1% consists of samples where the subject was blinking, moving, looking off-axis at the moment of capture, etc. The IREX 4 failure analysis found that matching failures for a similar iris dataset are almost entirely due to poor presentation of the iris.

Dataset: Operational Dataset 4th pull
Samples used: One eye
Enrolled Population: 1 million irides
Enrollment Method: One enrollment session per person
